1 Introduction

This is the Quarto template notebook for Lab 13 in the first Spring 2025 offering of DSC 011: Computing and Statistical Programming at UC Merced, with a focus on computing, visualizing, modeling and communicating interval estimates for sample proportions and means in R/tidyverse, and computing data science workflows with mixed R/tidyverse pipelines.

The text contains brief but self-contained introductions to statistics of interval estimation for proportions and means, some background on the Sex Ratio at Birth statistic, the importance and ethics of uncertainty estimation in data science communication, examples of using \(\LaTeX\) to write equations in markdown (which works in Quarto, RMarkdown, and Jupyter notebooks), a little on how to choose among different implementation strategies when computing data science workflows in the R/tidyverse. Finally, research on rank aggregation methods is presented and applied to create aggregate summaries of U.S. baby names over decades.

This file is distributed through git by pulling from the original DSC-011-Sp25-Baby-Names private template upstream repository, and appears at the top-level of the repository.

The content of this template Quarto file is Copyright (2025) David H. Ardell.

2.4 Interval Estimates for Sex Ratio in Baby Names Data by Decade

2.4.1 Top-200 Baby Names Data

2.4.1.1 Computing Credible Intervals for Sex Ratio by Decade
2.4.1.1.1 A Little Background on Sex Ratio at Birth

We previously computed the Sex Ratio at Birth (SRB) from the baby names data. The following code chunk prints its values on Render as a reminder:

sex_ratio_by_decade
    1880s     1890s     1900s     1910s     1920s     1930s     1940s     1950s 
0.4594740 0.3469095 0.3244410 0.4572775 0.4904915 0.5130107 0.5264436 0.5378342 
    1960s     1970s     1980s     1990s     2000s     2010s 
0.5480919 0.5636521 0.5656493 0.5706307 0.5849298 0.5783947

A more complete and self-descriptive name for this summary vector would have been proportion_boy_births_by_decade. But the name sex_ratio_by_decade is apt.

In demography and statistics on human births, the SRB \(\hat{p}_t\) in decade \(t\) is conventionally defined as the number (\(b_t\)) of boy babies born in that decade among a sample (\(n_t=b_t+g_t\)) of births in that decade (among those babies for whom sex has been unambiguously defined at birth), where \(g_t\) is the number of girl babies born in decade \(t\).

\[\hat{p_t} = \frac{b_t}{b_t+g_t}\]

2.4.1.1.2 The Importance of Interval Estimates in General

We symbolize the SRB here in decade \(t\) by \(\hat{p}_t\) to emphasize that it is a sample proportion, rate or relative frequency. The âhatâ means that \(\hat{p}_t\) is an estimate of an unknown population parameter, here a proportion or rate, assumed to be either independent and identically distributed or, more generally, exchangeable over the sample.

As shown at the top of Chapter 2 on Statistical Modeling in Holmes and Huber (2019), sample estimators of unknown population parameters are often symbolized with roman letters and hats, while their corresponding parameters are often symbolized by their greek letter homologous equivalents. Alternatively, greek letters are avoided entirely and estimates are symbolized by adding hats to roman letters symbolizing the population-level parameters. For example, unknown population proportions or rates are usually symbolized as either \(\pi\) or \(p\). The symbology makes clear that a population-level proprtion or rate is a probability in the frequentist sense. For more information on alternative definitions of probability and a fun self-quiz you can take to find out where you fall on the Bayesian-frequentist probability spectrum in your thinking, please see âChapter 1 The Big (Bayesian) Pictureâ in Johnson, Ott, and Dogucu (2022).

In previous work in DSC 011, we have only computed point estimates of the sample proportion of boy births by decade, but this is not sufficient for real data scientific work. This is because in general, when possible, we should always report interval estimates in addition to point estimates in our data scientific reports. This is a foundational criterion of ethical and reproducible data science and science in general.

In any scientific context we are obligated to report the uncertainties of our estimates, which, among other things, depend on sample sizes (\(n\)) through The Square Root Law: that is, uncertainty is inversely proportional to the square root of sample size \(n\). Put another way, you must sample four times as much data to cut the uncertainty (and width of an interval estimate) in half.

2.4.1.1.3 Interval Estimates for Proportions

The Central Limit Theorem (CLT) tells us that when sample size \(n\) becomes large enough, a sample mean (\(\bar{x}\)) is a normally distributed random variable that is a superior point estimate \(\mu\) and standard deviations (equal to the Standard Errors of the Mean), even when the underlying data that we computed a sample mean from are not themselves normally distributed. But the CLT does not tell us how large samples sizes have to be in order to achieve some specified level of certainty in our estimates.

Sample proportions are sample means. They are random sums of \(n > 1\) indicator or Bernoulli random variables that take the value 1 when an event of a certain category occurs and a value 0 when events of other categories occur.

Note

One-Hot Encoding uses as many indicator or Bernoulli random variables as there are factor levels in a categorical variable to achieve binary encoding of categorical random variables.

It turns out that Bayesian credible intervals are generally more accurate and the recommended interval estimates of sample proportions than frequentist confidence intervals based on the CLT, particularly when any of these conditions hold: the underlying parameter \(\pi\) is close in value to 0 or 1, sample size is limited, or there exists prior knowledge about the proportion being estimated.

For the sex ratio data, \(\pi \approx 0.5\) and sample sizes are large. In this case, the Bayesian credible intervals using a âflatâ (or Standard Uniform) prior distribution for \(\pi\) are expected to converge to the same upper and lower bounds as frequentist confidence intervals.

For your future reference, this section used \(\LaTeX\)-styled equations in Quarto markdown. \(\LaTeX\) equations are the standard way to write equations in RMarkdown and Quarto.

2.4.1.2 Visualizing Credible Intervals for Sex Ratio Data

Now we are ready to graph the interval estimates of sex ratio by decade.

  1. Down in the R Console, use the as_tibble() function on babies_born_by_decade_and_sex and pipe it to a graph expression that has these characteristics:
  1. Use aes() in the call to ggplot() to associate the aesthetics x with decade, y with sex_ratio.
  2. Use geom_errorbar() with an additional call to aes() to associate the aesthetic ymin with the name âlowerâ and ymax with the name âupperâ.
  3. Make the point estimates easier to see by extending the graph expression with calls to geom_point() and geom_line()
  4. Extend the graph expression with ylim() to set the y-axis limits to the values 0 and 1.
  5. Extend the graph expression with geom_hline(yintercept=0.5) to draw a reference line for an even sex ratio of 0.5.
  6. Extend the graph expression to add meaningful labels of âDecadeâ for the x-axis, âSex Ratio at Birth (SRB)â for the y-axis, âSex Ratio at Birth By Decade in Top-200 Baby Names Dataâ as a title, âBayesian Credible Intervals Shown Assuming a Flat Prior Distributionâ as a subtitle, and âData from U.S. Social Security Administration obtained April, 2025â as the caption.
  1. After you have perfected your graph expression in the Console, please copy it here to include the graph in your notebook:
as_tibble(babies_born_by_decade_and_sex) |>
  ggplot(aes(x = decade, y = sex_ratio)) +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = lower, ymax = upper)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_line() +
  ylim(0, 1) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0.5) +
  labs(x = "Decade", y = "Sex Ratio at Birth (SRB)", title = "Sex Ratio at Birth By Decade in Top-200 Baby Names Data", subtitle = "Bayesian Credible Intervals Shown Assuming a Flat Prior Distribution", caption = "Data from U.S. Social Security Administration obtained April, 2025")

Our graph appears to show a strong rejection of the prior hypothesis of an even sex ratio (\(H_0:\pi = 0.5\)). But how much of the fluctuation in sex ratio by decade is from limited sampling of births? What is the true value of the SRB in humans?

In this exercise, since we are using a tidyverse tibble, we will practice using the tidyverse to compute summary statistics.

  5. Use up-arrow command-line editing to extend your tidyverse pipeline with another call to mutate() to add a column called sex_ratio to the tibble and assign the return value to a tibble with the name babies_born_by_decade_and_sex_full.
  1. Once you have correctly completed all the previous steps, copy your assignment tidyverse pipeline to the following code chunk to test its value. Tidyverse will issue a warning âsummarise()` has grouped output by âdecadeâ.â that you are free to ignore.
babies_born_by_decade_and_sex_full <- babynames |>
  mutate(decade = year %/% 10 * 10) |>
  group_by(decade, sex) |>
  summarize(freq = sum(n), .groups = "drop_last") |>
  pivot_wider(names_from = sex, values_from = freq) |>
  mutate(total = F + M) |>
  mutate(sex_ratio = M / total)
try(digest::digest(babies_born_by_decade_and_sex_full |>

2.5 Popularity over Decades: Aggregating Rank Statistics Over Decades: Top-200 Baby Names Data

Letâs regenerate the Lollipop Chart of mean ranks of names over decades.

names_by_mean_rank <- mean_rank_by_name_and_sex[order(mean_rank_by_name_and_sex$mean_rank),]
names_by_mean_rank$rank <- 1:1236

      theme(legend.position.inside = c(0.92, 0.86))

This is a very crude method to aggregate rank data over decades, because it fails to take uncertainty into account. That is, the amount of data that we have for each name varies. Some names might have been popular in only one decade or a few decades, while other names could have been popular in all 14 decades. In computing the mean ranks or overall ppopularity of names over decades, we want to take the sample sizes, that is, the number of decades names in which decades are ranked, into account. One way to do this is to visualize confidence intervals for the mean ranks.

2.5.1 Calculating Confidence Intervals for Mean Ranks of Names Over Decades

We can use the base-R function called t.test() to compute confidence or credible intervals for both sample means and for differences in two sample means, whether they are paired or independent.

  1. To get a feel for using the t.test() function for a one-sample confidence interval for a sample mean, run the following code chunk:
t.test(c(1,15,24),conf.level = 0.99)

The table shows that confidence intervals vary widely for these mean ranks, sometimes to very extreme values, often include negative values for the lower bound (which do not make sense for rank data) and often are NA. Aggregating rank data over decades through the mean-rank is very noisy and seems to not work well. We need to find alternative approaches that work better for rank aggregation.

2.5.3 Better Rank Aggregation of Baby Names Data over Decades

In a study on Rank Aggregation methods, Li, Wang, and Xiao (2017) found that the generally best performing algorithm and implementation over a range of scenarios studied was the Borda count method using an aggregation function over the geometric mean of ranks as implemented in the R package TopKLists (Schimek et al. 2015). In their analysis they particularly examined the case of a Top-K only list such as in our top-200 Baby names data.

The Borda count method is an extremely old method. You can read more about it at the Borda count wikipedia page.

in order to use TopKLists::Borda() we need to make a list of vectors of boys or girls names for each decade and sex in the data. One easy way to make new lists from data-frames, conditioned on a factor, is through the split() function as we previously saw in Lab 10.

  1. Follow these steps in the RConsole to aggregate ranks over decades for the boys and girls names, while seeing how the data is transformed step-by-step:
  1. Call split() on baby_clean as first argument and baby_clean_f$decade as second argument and save it to a list called sp.
  2. Create a list of vectors of boys names for each decade in rank order with the code do.call(list,lapply(sp,function(x)x$boy_name)) and save it to a list named boys
  3. Create a list of vectors of girls names for each decade in rank order with the code do.call(list,lapply(sp,function(x)x$girl_name)) and save it to a list named girls
  4. Combine the two lists into one with the function boys_girls = c(boys,girls)
  5. Validate your work with the call str(boys_girls).
  6. Call Borda(boys_girls)
  7. Save the return value to the variable Borda_top200.
  1. Save your validated code for defining Borda_top200 in the code chunk below to test the value:
try(digest::digest(Borda_top200$Scores |> 
                 mutate(across(where(is_double),round,digits=7)))  ==
  "a298d2fea5f44e5f1a0ddf1d6baeb8b7"
)
